li.p:
 For \(m > 1\), let \(p(m)\) be \(a^{n+m}=a^n*a^m\) for all \(n\geq 1\). The basis for this proof follows directly from the basis for the definition
of exponentiation.



Induction: Assume that for some \(m > 1\), \(p(m)\) is true. Then



\(\textrm{                 }a^{n+(m+1)}= a^{(n+m)+1}\textrm{    }\textrm{ by} \textrm{ the} \textrm{ associativity} \textrm{ of} \textrm{ integer} \textrm{ addition}\quad
\quad =a^{n+m}*a^1\text \textrm{ by} \textrm{ the} \textrm{ definition} \textrm{ of} \textrm{ exponentiation}\quad \quad =\left(a^n*a^m\right)*a^1\text \textrm{ by}
\textrm{ the} \textrm{ induction} \textrm{ hypothesis}\quad \quad = a^n*\left(a^m*a^1\right)\textrm{    }\textrm{ by} \textrm{ associativity}\quad \quad = a^n*a^{m+1}\textrm{ 
 }\textrm{ by} \textrm{ the} \textrm{ definition} \textrm{ of} \textrm{ exponentiation}\)

 Let \(p(m)\)be \(\left(a^n\right)^m= a^{n m}\) for all integers n.



Basis: \(\left(a^m\right)^0= e\) and \(a^{m\cdot 0}=a^0= e\) therefore, \(p(0)\) is true.



Induction; Assume that \(p(m)\) is true for some \(m >\)0,



\(\quad \left(a^n\right)^{m+1}=\left(a^n\right)^m*a^n\textrm{     }\textrm{ definition} \textrm{ of} \textrm{ exponentiation}\quad \quad =a^{n m}*a^n\textrm{ 
      }\textrm{ by} \textrm{ the} \textrm{ induction} \textrm{ hypothesis}\quad \quad =a^{n m + n}\textrm{           }\textrm{ by} \textrm{ part} (a) \textrm{ of} \textrm{ this}
\textrm{ problem}\quad \quad =a^{n(m+1)}\textrm{           }\)



Finally, if m is negative, we can verify that \(\left(a^n\right)^m= a^{n m}\) using many of the same steps as the proof of part (a).
